<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-914-540  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 914 540.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  August 28 1989 v3 n35 p48(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Wiring standard promotes flexibility in comm applications.andO;(communications)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Glassco, Rick.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Since the divestiture of the Bell system, government agencies havehad to take responsibility for wiring their own buildings, withoutstandards or guidance.andP;  The Electronics IndustriesAssociation/Telecommunications Industry Association has, however,released for comment and approval a new standard designed inconjunction with the new 41.8.3 standard for buildingarchitectures to support wiring.andP;  This new wiring standard wouldbe used on all General Services Administration buildings underconstruction.andP;  The standard will provide a flexible, highperformance system that will be effective across most existingtechnologies.andP;  The standard calls for the use of twisted pairwiring as the basic technology, but support for the future use offiber-optic cable will also be a built-in feature.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TelecommunicationsStandardizationUnited States. General Services AdministrationTwisted PairFiber OpticsConnectivityCables.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>